In Java, you should typically use the `equals()` method to compare the value of two string objects, rather than using the `==` operator. The reason for this is that the `==` operator checks if the two objects being compared are the exact same object in memory, while the `equals()` method checks if the values of the two objects are equivalent.

For example, consider the following code:

```
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";

if (str1 == str2) {
   System.out.println("The strings are the same!");
} else {
   System.out.println("The strings are different!");
}
```

In this case, the `==` operator will return `false`, because `str1` and `str2` are not the same object in memory. However, if you use the `equals()` method instead:

```
String str1 = "Hello";
String str2 = "Hello";

if (str1.equals(str2)) {
   System.out.println("The strings are the same!");
} else {
   System.out.println("The strings are different!");
}
```

